ative movement in this country. As The Vanishing Tradition shows, the conservative movement has not often retrieved its wounded, instead dispatching them in order to please its friendly opposition and to prove its "moderateness." The movement has also been open to the influence of demanding sponsors who have pushed it in sometimes bizarre directions. Finally, the essayists here, highlight the movement's appeal to "permanent values" as a truly risible gesture, given how arduously its celebrities have worked to catch up with the Left on social issues. This no-holds-barred critical examination of American conservatism opens debates and seeks controversy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aConservatismzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 4aCurrent Events. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Libertarianism .2bisacsh  aDeclaration of Independence, Dennis Prager, Russell Kirk, Douglas Murray, Big Con, Dinesh D'Souza.1 aCathey, Boyd D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotto, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrummond, Nicholas W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottfried, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottfried, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHavers, Grant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawley, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffrey, Marjorie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerwick, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcy, Richard T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular